               as
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\lambda \rightarrow 0$ \end{document}
               . Note that the transformation is applied to variables that arenotdummy variables (see, e.g., Greene1997).

The heteroscedastic specification is
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mathrm{Var}\,( \varepsilon ) =( \sigma ^{2}) [ w^{2}] ^{( \lambda ) }$ \end{document}
               , wherewis the fund duration. This heteroscedastic specification was employed for the estimates of portfolio size (only8) in panel A of tables6and7to account for the possibility of unobserved observations in the data (see n. 4 and accompanying text). The likelihood dominance criterion (Davidson and MacKinnon1993, 492) indicated that this heteroscedastic Box‐Cox transformation outperformed other specifications (reported and otherwise). For example, the likelihood ratio statistic is equal to 307.25 fortable 6(panel A) (comparing models 1 and 2), which is significant at the 1% level. (The reported log likelihood values are directly comparable across transformations within each panel.) The likelihood ratio statistics support the Box‐Cox specifications in panel A of tables6and7, but the tests are inconclusive for distinguishing between the models in panel B of tables6and7. Alternative specifications (not presented, but available on request) did not perform better than the heteroscedastic Box‐Cox specification (model 1 in tables6and7).

Consistent with Kanniainen and Keuschnigg (2003,2004), there is a positive and significant (at the 1% level) relation between the number of VC managers and the number of entrepreneurial firms in the VC fund’s portfolio (seeSec. II.A
               ). Adding one VC manager in the full sample of funds (table 6, panel A) gives rise to approximately two additional entrepreneurial firms in the fund’s portfolio, but it would take an extra eight limited partnership VC fund managers to increase portfolio size by two entrepreneurial firms (
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $8\times 0.266$ \end{document}
               ; seetable 7, panel A). The evidence thus indicates that limited partnership VC managers have a more active role in their entrepreneurial investees. More generally, the evidence provides very strong support for the proposition that the characteristics of the VC fund affect the size of the VC portfolio.

The coefficients for the proportion of all investments that are staged and syndicated (Sec. II.C
               ) are negative and significant at the 1% level in each of panels A and B of tables6and7. Specifically, increasing staging frequency by 10% across all types of funds (table 6, panel A) leads to a decrease in portfolio size by approximately 2.6 entrepreneurial firms (
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $0.10\times -25.932$ \end{document}
               ); by comparison, it would require an increase in staging frequency by 30% to give rise to a decrease in portfolio size by two entrepreneurial firms for the private independent funds (table 7, panel A). Syndicating an additional 10% of investments leads to an average of 2.5 fewer entrepreneurial firms in the portfolios of all types of VCs (table 6, panel A) but only 0.4 fewer entrepreneurial firm in a private independent limited partnership VC portfolio (table 7, panel A). Similarly, a 10% increase in staging and syndication frequency lowers the rate of portfolio expansion by approximately 0.2 entrepreneurial firm per manager per year among all types of funds (table 6, panel B) and by 0.1 entrepreneurial firm per manager per year among the limited partnerships (table 7, panel B). The staging coefficient is consistent with the proposition that more intensive monitoring by the VC gives rise to fewer entrepreneurial firms in the VC portfolio (see also Gompers1995). The syndication coefficient is somewhat surprising because syndication facilitates risk sharing, monitoring, and screening (Lerner1994) and therefore may enable larger portfolios (PMB shifts up; seefig. 1). In this data set, the syndication coefficient points to the greater importance of agency problems among syndicated investors (i.e., free‐riding and misrepresentation of information between lead inside and follow‐on outside VCs [see Lerner1994]), which exacerbates the costs of adding another entrepreneurial firm to a portfolio (PMC shifts up, and this effect more than offsets the move in the PMB curve; seefig. 1). PMC is higher because each VC must monitor other syndicated VC investors, and not just the entrepreneur.

The results also provide the first look at empirical evidence on portfolio size and returns to scale in VC finance. The CVCA data indicate that returns to scale are in fact diminishing (
